<h1 class="hero-h">AI agents for business: <em>the 2026 buyer's playbook.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">AI agents have moved from demos to production. This is the practical playbook for B2B companies: where agents earn their keep, the tools to start with, the operating model, and what to keep humans in.</p>
<div class="verdict"><div class="verdict-l">Short version</div><p class="verdict-p">Start with agents for one or two well-scoped, repeatable workflows: lead qualification, customer-success triage, content production at scale, or research and summarization. Use Claude or ChatGPT Team as the base, layer Zapier or Make for orchestration, and put a named human owner on the agent. Budget $200-$2,000/mo. ROI is usually positive within 60 days for the right use cases.</p></div>
</div></div>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">Where AI agents earn their keep in a B2B company</h2>
<p class="body">Agents are at their best on workflows that are repeatable, document-and-text-heavy, and forgiving of a quick human review. Reach for them when the work has shape but no judgment-critical decisions.</p>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Lead qualification and enrichment.</strong> Read inbound leads, enrich with public data, score against your ICP, and queue the qualified ones for a human SDR with a personalized opener. The right agent here often doubles the rate at which good leads get a fast first touch.</li>
<li><strong>Customer success triage and summarization.</strong> Listen to support tickets and call recordings, summarize, categorize, and surface the at-risk accounts. Frees CS managers from the admin and concentrates them on the saves.</li>
<li><strong>Content production at scale.</strong> Brief, draft, edit, and adapt content across channels (blog, email, social, sales enablement) with consistent brand voice. The agent does the production; humans approve direction and final.</li>
<li><strong>Research and competitive intelligence.</strong> Continuously monitor competitors, customers, and market signals; produce weekly briefings rather than ad-hoc scrambles. Agents that read across sources are dramatically better than humans at the breadth here.</li>
</ul>
<p class="body">The pattern: pick a workflow with clear inputs, clear outputs, and a human review step. Avoid agents for judgment-only work or work where the cost of being wrong is high.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">Recommended starting stack</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Claude Pro or Team ($20-$30/seat)</strong> or <strong>ChatGPT Team</strong> as the reasoning and writing base.</li>
<li><strong>Zapier or Make ($30-$200/mo)</strong> for orchestration between your CRM, email, and the agent.</li>
<li><strong>A dedicated agent platform</strong> (Lindy, Relay, or similar) if you want a no-code agent builder.</li>
<li><strong>Your existing CRM and helpdesk</strong> as the data sources and write targets.</li>
</ul>
<p class="body">Most mid-market B2B companies run this stack for $200 to $2,000 per month, with the spread driven by seat count and agent volume.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">The ROI math</h2>
<p class="body">Pick one workflow, baseline the time it currently takes (hours per week), and measure. A lead-qualification agent that returns a personalized first touch within 5 minutes typically lifts qualified-meeting rate by 15-30 percent against a 24-hour-response baseline; that one improvement often pays for the full stack within a quarter.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">What AI agents should not do for your business</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li>Send client communications without a human review step. The relationship is the product.</li>
<li>Make final pricing, legal, or contract decisions without your judgment.</li>
<li>Replace the senior strategic role. Agents execute; humans set direction.</li>
<li>Run unattended for more than a week without an owner reviewing outputs and iterating prompts.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">Frequently asked questions</h2>
<div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">What is the difference between an AI agent and a chatbot?</div><div class="faq-a">A chatbot answers messages. An agent takes actions: pulls data, makes API calls, updates records, sends emails, and chains steps to complete a task. The bar for 'agent' is whether it acts, not just whether it talks.</div></div>
<div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">How much do AI agents cost for a B2B company?</div><div class="faq-a">Most mid-market B2B companies budget $200 to $2,000 per month for the stack (assistant + orchestration + agent platform). The wider variance is in setup and iteration time, which is usually the under-budgeted line item.</div></div>
<div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">Which workflow should I start with?</div><div class="faq-a">Pick one that is repeatable, document-heavy, and forgiving. Lead qualification, content production, and customer-success triage are the three that almost always work.</div></div>
<div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">Do AI agents replace SDRs or CSMs?</div><div class="faq-a">Not the senior roles. Agents take the repetitive admin off SDRs and CSMs so they can focus on conversations. The team usually stays the same size and ships more output.</div></div>
<div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">Who owns the agent in my company?</div><div class="faq-a">Pick a named person. Without an owner, agents drift in 90 days. The owner reviews outputs, updates prompts, and reports on metrics.</div></div>
</div></section>

